                      <div align="center">
                        <table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="80%">
                          <tr>
                            <td width="100%" bgcolor="#004242">
                              <p align="center" style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 150%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0"><b><font size="2" face="Tahoma" color="#FFFFFF">DESCRIPTION</font></b></td>
                          </tr>
                          <tr><td width="100%">
                              <p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0">&nbsp;</td>
                          </tr>
                          <tr>
                            <td width="100%">
                              <p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0"><font size="2" face="Tahoma">
Everfrost, grandest newbie zone on Antonica.
<br><br>
<b>Primary hotspots</b>
<br><br>
Halas - Home, vendors, wenches, etc<br>
3 guard - Guards, one of the tundra entrances<br>
1 guard - Home of Bandl, god of the tundra. Other entrance to the tundra<br>
3 igloos - large open area in the peaks, lots of stuff to slaughter<br>
Blackburrow - Gnollville, good XP if you know what you're doing<br>
Flattop - small mountain near Bandl, clear of wanderers. Good place to sit a group at<br>
The point - outcropping near Bandle, another good spot for a group<br>
Megan's tower - East of 3 guard, where Megan O'Reilly services orcs...<br>
South tower - South of Megan's, Southeast of Bandl. Typical spot to hang out<br>
Statue - East of Megan's, little bit south. Landmark<br>
Orc temple - Where the icy orcs and Redwind chill<br>
Permafrost - Northeast end of the zone, can't miss it. Ice giants at the door
<br><br>
<b>How to get to places</b>
<br><br>
All paths start from Halas unless specified.
<br><br>
3 guard - head down the ramp, and out the canyon. Turn left, and head straight until you get to a fork. Veer right, and head down the canyon, and you will reach 3 guard<br>
3 igloos - head down the ramp, out the canyon. Follow the canyon to the right, and head straight. Ignore the two turnoffs to your right, they're dead ends. Go right at the fork, and you will arrive at the igloos<br>
1 guard - turn left at the last fork before the igloos, follow the canyon east<br>
Blackburrow - go straight across the igloo area, follow the canyon around. Ignore the two short dead ends on your right as you round the large boulder, then keep the wall on your right and you will see the ramp<br>
Tundra places - go by the list above, and get to know the place
<br><br>
<b>The Peaks</b>
<br><br>
This is the area cornered by Halas, 3 guard, 1 guard, and blackburrow. Also known as the maze. There is a constant stream of mobs between levels 1 and 4 running around here, slaughter them all and you'll be level 5 in nothing flat. Ice goblins will help each other, skels will help each other, bear cubs will help each other, as will wolves. Past that most of them are non aggro. There are a few ice goblin camps in here, good camping most of the time, if a little slow to spawn. Watch out for the vengeful skeletons, as they are aggro, and range in level from 9-14 or so. Nasty critters.
<br><br>
The 5 or 6 guards at the entrance to Blackburrow are good XP.
<br><br>
The peaks are an excellent hunting spot for any melee-centric class from level 1-5 or so. Casters have a bit harder time, as they aren't built to deal with a long steady chain of mobs that bring friends.
<br><br>
<b>The Tundra</b>
<br><br>
The rest of the zone is a large open area with few landmarks, and a lot of wanderers. Ice goblin scouts and snow wolves show up out here for the 5-6 level range, with two small goblin camps to supplement that. One is between 3 guard and 1 guard, follow the right wall from 3 guard. The other is in the southwest corner, follow the wall right from 1 guard.
<br><br>
Between 6 and 9-10, your main fare is made up of skeletons, polar bears, large spiders, and snow orc troopers. Plop your group down at a nice landmark, the point and flattop work well, and find some live bait (tank type most likely) to go fishing.
<br><br>
Around 9, you can start hunting calves with a group. They become soloable around 12. Avoid momma's like the plague (can't miss em, even bigger than calves, hit for 40 or so...) Calves and mommas will run to assist any of their brethren that are under fire, which means you want to avoid the main paths.
<br><br>
The mammoth highways run roughly north/south right in front of Bandl, one east/west near the south edge, and some more north/south near the river. Occasionally there will be a large herd of them near the south tower, which can be bad if you pull a calf through there. Spirit of Wolf is required.
<br><br>
As you go up in level, add mountaineers to the list of things to slaughter. They tend to be in about the same level range as the calves. Orc shamans are hell on two legs though, they tend to be around level 14-16ish, and can usually root. Watch out for them when pulling or soloing, as they can ruin your day REAL quick.
<br><br>
There are one or two ice bones here as well, usually on the river or in the southern area near the south tower. These can only be hit by magic weapons, which may or may not be a problem for you. It's less of an issue now, but back when combines were Pimpin...
<br><br>
Groups in the low to mid 20's can start challenging the icy orcs at the temple. There are about half a dozen of them here, so thing can get sticky if the snow hits the fan. Mommas become viable targets around level 30, though they tend to be in short supply.
<br><br>
Up at the high 40's, you can start playing with ice giants if you wish, though they tend to be camped by soloing druids.
<br><br>
<b>Specials</b>
<br><br>
The Dark Assassin occasionally wanders through, avoid him. Martar Icebear is another nasty. Karg Icebear has a quest for a cloak, if you bring him 5 plat and a polar bear skin. He also drops the Gigantic Zweihander, but since the release of Kunark, demand for this has fallen off a bit. Tundra Jack and his pet bear Iceberg wander the tundra, and are related to the Langseax quest.
<br><br>
There are some caves under the river, if you happen to have enduring breath. There is not much in them though, aside from a large bear needed for a shaman quest and a cleric quest. Watch your step though, as there's a level 50-60 NPC wizard down here that doesn't like visitors. He stays in one spot though, so if you have infravision or some other form of nightvision it isn't too difficult to avoid him.
<br><br>
The Ice Comet quest people are on the north wall of the tundra.
<br><br>
<b>MadKynes<br>
The Rathe</b>
                           </font></td>
                          </tr>
